{"type":"message","id":"214a3932","parentId":"f71b98b4","timestamp":"2026-03-11T16:43:24.754Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"**Considering record creation**\n\nI need to batch-create records with timestamps in milliseconds, and while 29 records feel a bit lengthy, it seems manageable. Using Python could simplify crafting the JSON payload from search results. Maybe I could directly call the tool since we already have results. However, if local transformations aren't useful, maybe I should just focus on fewer records. It looks like using ISO strings might be easier, but the user has requested a bitable format, so I will stick to that!\n\n**Simplifying record creation**\n\nI’m thinking of using exec to convert all ISO strings from the search output if I paste a compact JSON list. This could help in outputting the records as a JSON snippet. I still need to call the tool with an object from the results, and I’m considering crafting 29 records manually, potentially omitting timestamps. While date fields might be optional, they'll still be useful. To simplify, I can focus on title, link, document type, and owner/editor. I’ll leave timestamps blank since the schema has those fields. Let’s go with 29 records without timestamps!","thinkingSignature":"{\"id\":\"rs_0ca5b223d5a1af220169b19b66f8908191b373350880e21948\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABpsZtzZwgrbtGGhoGtFEcGv6URHfsdRxuJKOH7w7EkxvjYuvmtKaxUxbBLjbUtl3UDUFjJ-ZX5PaNWDhS6_9MxHvtp4gRtkoJsDn9888-mF73DrcpA-uP7XZOElSrQvHQavhuqhCePox4nWvTmWYO9W_9o2b5dvWY9pj1b5BmXo3RjLqsFHlYRGP3Z4WVunC7PV4CBYOtjY4ezaGBK9JmnzBMj6Ikj0lJx_Y6I6PDAQLsq5EYk5YiVJPeSGTPnLYGE_eiSWmseOWF8wbp7jtxJH8xgdyfzZJJ6CCn24ySbMb80_XWagEKTMQnfOi7ldUTe6BUVE9_6rzN8vG00RA1Xer_K2MQnmOWLMnPjbgEOkYfFRSuzVf-TXdkMO4YY7AckpCHC6ZatVOf7uHrtGAl2RlqC8TCaOK3_hXPFg3DPMNNDPtO36GEHmn3J0NZ9GU1yW6JllFRM144iksOVdfRxhKQJQ4SLalwPgHu6_JzFW74gh_z_I2dEXOmUFCirM6mFWe8szjjbyXmov5-D7FGIqVW5QN1GTgeWIzTpl6Ct_YdWdGMqCLcELGOJnJ88QuNA